'''Marguerite Dupire''' (12 October 1920 – 4 March 2015) was a [[French people|French]] [[Ethnology|ethnologist]] who specialises on [[Ethnic groups of Africa|African people]], and had worked extensively on the [[Fula people|Fulani]] of [[Niger]], [[Cameroon]], [[Guinea]], [[Senegal]], and then after a mission in [[Ivory Coast]], on the [[Serer people]] of [[Kingdom of Sine|Sine]] (in Senegal) since 1965.<ref name="Worso">Le Worso</ref><ref name="Bio"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Marguerite Dupire (1920-2015)|url=http://data.bnf.fr/12386359/marguerite_dupire/|publisher=Bibliothèque nationale de France|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref>
==Biography== Dupire gained a degree in [[philosophy]] in 1943. She then completed her training by studying [[psychology]] and [[ethnology]] at the [[University of Paris]], then in the [[United States]], at the [[Northwestern University]] and the [[Philadelphia University]], where she was the student of notable [[anthropologists]] such as [[Melville J. Herskovits|Melville Herskovits]] and [[Alfred Irving Hallowell]] in the late 1940s.<ref name="Worso"/><ref name="Bio">Bibliographie thématique de Marguerite Dupire</ref>
